{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_018oL9CJLtgcw4VNpQTEmJs2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have all the information I need to compile a comprehensive audit report. Let me write up the findings.\n\nKey findings:\n1. **Cluster Health**: 3-node cluster (rabbitmq-0, 1, 2), all running, no alarms, no network partitions\n2. **Version**: RabbitMQ 3.12.14 on Erlang 25.3.2.15 - This is out of support (the status command says \"RabbitMQ release series support status: out of support\")\n3. **Virtual Hosts**: Two vhosts: `/` (default) and `/app`\n4. **Users and Permissions**: The `admin` user has full administrator privileges across both vhosts, while `app-user` is restricted to the `/app` vhost with full permissions there but no access to the default vhost.\n5. **Policies**: No policies are configured on either vhost, meaning there's no HA setup or other policy-based configurations in place.\n6. **Queues and Network**: The `/app` vhost has one durable classic queue (`app-queue`) with no messages or consumers, while the default vhost has no queues. TLS is disabled entirely—AMQP runs on plaintext port 5672 and the management API uses HTTP on port 15672.\n7. **Guest user and cluster settings**: The guest user is configured to accept connections from any network rather than just loopback, though it may have been removed from the system. The cluster is set to use `pause_minority` for partition handling, which is a sensible safety measure.\n8. **Plugins and feature flags**: Management and Kubernetes peer discovery plugins are enabled, along with standard features like quorum and stream queues, but federation, shovel, and LDAP are absent. The StatefulSet has no resource limits defined.\n9. **Exchanges, bindings, and security**: Only default exchanges exist on `/app`, with `app-queue` bound to the default exchange using its own name as the routing key. There are no vhost or user-level limits, SHA-256 password hashing is in place, but the credentials obfuscation fallback uses a weak default value (\"nocookie\").\n\nNow I'm identifying the security issues. RabbitMQ 3.12.14 is no longer supported and needs upgrading. The cluster lacks TLS entirely—AMQP traffic on 5672 is unencrypted and the management API runs over plain HTTP. The `loopback_users.guest = false` setting is problematic since the guest user might still exist despite not appearing in the user list. More critically, there's no HA or quorum policy protecting `app-queue`, so in this 3-node cluster the queue data isn't replicated. The `app-user` also has overly broad permissions with full configure access across all resources.\n\nBeyond that, the pods have no resource limits defined, the credentials obfuscation secret is set to a weak default value, and the management UI is exposed without TLS protection. There are no policies in place for message TTL, queue length limits, or dead-letter routing. I need to document these findings and then generate the ConfigMap.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":553,"cache_read_input_tokens":37457,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":553},"output_tokens":11,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5fb079ae-f54d-4b57-aaf3-f58657c3fae1","uuid":"1e4ce6e8-ae17-44d2-9bc8-40f5e85a762f","request_id":"req_011Cc2hkyusDC4TKBPPEzZp9"}
