{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_018oL9CJLtgcw4VNpQTEmJs2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01WMjHiFqVjRF9dGPxNv5SDF","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/tmp/findings.txt","content":"RabbitMQ Read-Only Compliance Audit\n=====================================\nNamespace:  karma-rabbitmq-readonly-audit-20260614-064520\nAudit date: 2026-06-14\nAuditor:    Automated read-only inspection (no changes made)\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n1. CLUSTER HEALTH & TOPOLOGY\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nNodes (all disk nodes, all running):\n  rabbit@rabbitmq-0.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local\n  rabbit@rabbitmq-1.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local\n  rabbit@rabbitmq-2.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local\n\nActive alarms:        none\nNetwork partitions:   none\nMaintenance status:   none of the three nodes under maintenance\nTotal memory used:    ~154 MB (watermark at 40% of available RAM, ~5.4 GB)\nFree disk space:      ~884 GB (watermark 50 MB)\nTotal connections:    0\nTotal queues:         1 (in /app)\n\n[OK] Cluster is healthy: 3/3 nodes running, no alarms, no partitions.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n2. VERSION & SUPPORT STATUS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nRabbitMQ version:   3.12.14   (image: rabbitmq:3.12-management)\nErlang/OTP version: 25.3.2.15\n\n[FINDING - HIGH] RabbitMQ 3.12 is out of support per the official release\ncalendar. No further security patches will be issued for this series. The\ncluster should be upgraded to a currently supported release series (3.13.x or\n4.x at time of writing).\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n3. VIRTUAL HOSTS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nConfigured vhosts:\n  /       (default)\n  /app    (custom application vhost)\n\nNo vhost-level connection or queue-count limits are set on either vhost.\n\n[OK] Default vhost and application vhost are separated.\n[FINDING - LOW] No resource limits (max-connections, max-queues) are applied\nto either vhost, which could allow a single client to exhaust broker resources.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n4. USERS & TAGS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nUser        Tags\n----------  ----------------\nadmin       [administrator]\napp-user    (none)\n\nThe built-in \"guest\" user does not appear in the user list — it has been\nremoved (or was never present). This is correct practice.\n\n[OK] Only two users are defined; the default guest user is absent.\n[OK] admin is tagged as administrator; app-user carries no elevated tags.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n5. USER PERMISSIONS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nVhost /  (default):\n  User     Configure  Write  Read\n  -------  ---------  -----  ----\n  admin    .*         .*     .*\n\nVhost /app:\n  User      Configure  Write  Read\n  --------  ---------  -----  ----\n  admin     .*         .*     .*\n  app-user  .*         .*     .*\n\n[OK] app-user has access only to /app, not to the default vhost.\n[FINDING - MEDIUM] app-user holds full configure permission (pattern \".*\") on\n/app. Application service accounts typically require only write + read\npermissions and should not be able to declare or delete exchanges, queues, or\nbindings at runtime. Consider tightening the configure pattern to \"\" (empty) or\na narrow allowlist matching only queues this user must manage.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n6. POLICIES\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nNo policies are defined on either vhost (/ or /app).\n\n[FINDING - MEDIUM] Without policies there is no enforcement of:\n  - Queue high-availability / replication (classic queues have no HA policy;\n    see queue finding below).\n  - Message TTL (dead messages accumulate indefinitely).\n  - Queue length limits (unbounded growth possible under backpressure).\n  - Dead-letter routing (failed/expired messages are silently dropped).\nSecurity teams should consider whether absence of these policies meets the\norganisation's data-retention and availability requirements.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n7. QUEUES\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nVhost /app:\n  Name       Type     Durable  State    Messages  Consumers\n  ---------  -------  -------  -------  --------  ---------\n  app-queue  classic  true     running  0         0\n\nVhost / (default): no queues.\n\n[OK] app-queue is durable — it survives broker restarts.\n[FINDING - MEDIUM] app-queue is a classic (non-quorum) queue with no HA policy.\nIn a 3-node cluster this means queue data is stored on a single node's disk; if\nthat node fails, the queue and its messages are unavailable until the node\nrecovers. For workloads requiring high availability, this queue should be\nconverted to a quorum queue (x-queue-type: quorum) or covered by a classic\nmirroring policy. (Quorum queue feature flag is enabled on this cluster.)\n\n[OK] No auto-delete queues are present; app-queue persists without active consumers.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n8. EXCHANGES (vhost /app)\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nOnly the standard built-in AMQP exchanges are present — no custom exchanges:\n  (default)         direct    durable\n  amq.direct        direct    durable\n  amq.fanout        fanout    durable\n  amq.headers       headers   durable\n  amq.match         headers   durable\n  amq.topic         topic     durable\n  amq.rabbitmq.trace topic    durable\n\n[OK] No unexpected or custom exchanges are defined.\n[NOTE] amq.rabbitmq.trace is present (it is always present but inactive unless\nthe Firehose trace plugin is enabled). Confirm that tracing is not active in\nproduction (would log all message payloads to the trace exchange).\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n9. TLS / ENCRYPTION IN TRANSIT\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nListeners configured:\n  Port 5672   protocol: amqp          (plaintext AMQP 0-9-1)\n  Port 15672  protocol: http          (plaintext HTTP Management API)\n  Port 25672  protocol: clustering    (inter-node / CLI)\n\nTLS listener list: [] (empty — TLS is not enabled)\nSSL options:       [] (no certificate or CA paths configured)\n\n[FINDING - HIGH] AMQP traffic on port 5672 is unencrypted. All messages,\ncredentials (username + password sent with every connection), and channel\ndata are transmitted in plaintext. Any entity with network access can\nintercept or tamper with broker traffic.\n\n[FINDING - HIGH] The Management API (port 15672) is served over plain HTTP.\nAdmin credentials and API responses (which include full queue/user/policy\ndata) are transmitted in plaintext.\n\nRecommended remediation: configure TLS listeners on 5671 (AMQPS) and 15671\n(HTTPS Management), supply a valid certificate/key pair via a Kubernetes\nSecret, and disable or restrict the plaintext listeners.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n10. AUTHENTICATION & SECURITY SETTINGS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nPassword hashing algorithm: rabbit_password_hashing_sha256  [OK]\nloopback_users.guest = false  — guest user (if it existed) would be\n  reachable from any network host, not just loopback. Because the guest\n  user has been removed, this setting carries no immediate risk, but the\n  explicit \"false\" value would be dangerous if guest were re-created.\n  [NOTE] Consider setting loopback_users.guest = true or leaving it\n  unset (the default is \"loopback only\") as a defence-in-depth measure.\n\ncredentials_obfuscation_fallback_secret: \"nocookie\" — this is the\n  Erlang cookie default/placeholder value.\n  [FINDING - LOW] The credential obfuscation fallback secret should be\n  rotated to a unique, randomly generated value per deployment. Using the\n  default weakens at-rest obfuscation of stored credentials.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n11. CLUSTER PARTITION HANDLING\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\ncluster_partition_handling = pause_minority\n\n[OK] pause_minority is the recommended setting for a 3-node cluster. The\nminority partition (1 node) pauses rather than forming a split-brain cluster,\npreserving data consistency.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n12. PLUGINS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nEnabled:\n  rabbitmq_management           — HTTP API and web UI\n  rabbitmq_management_agent     — per-node stats collection\n  rabbitmq_peer_discovery_k8s   — Kubernetes-native cluster formation\n  rabbitmq_peer_discovery_common — peer discovery base\n  rabbitmq_web_dispatch         — cowboy HTTP dispatcher\n  amqp_client / cowboy / cowlib  — supporting libraries\n\n[OK] No Shovel, Federation, LDAP, or OAuth2 plugins are enabled — attack\nsurface is minimal.\n[OK] Peer discovery uses the Kubernetes API; no static hostlist or DNS seed\nis required.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n13. KUBERNETES RESOURCE LIMITS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nStatefulSet resource requests/limits: not set (resources: {})\n\n[FINDING - LOW] Without CPU and memory requests/limits, the RabbitMQ pods\ncan consume unbounded node resources and may be OOM-killed under load without\npredictable behaviour. Define appropriate requests and limits for the\nproduction workload profile.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n14. SECRETS PRESENT IN NAMESPACE\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n  rabbitmq-admin          (Opaque, 2 keys — admin credentials)\n  rabbitmq-app            (Opaque, 2 keys — app-user credentials)\n  rabbitmq-erlang-cookie  (Opaque, 1 key — inter-node auth cookie)\n\n[OK] Credentials are stored as Kubernetes Secrets rather than embedded in\nConfigMaps or environment literals.\n[NOTE] Secrets are not encrypted at rest by default in Kubernetes unless\netcd encryption is configured at the cluster level. Confirm that etcd\nencryption is enabled in the host cluster if this is a compliance requirement.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nSUMMARY OF FINDINGS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nSeverity  Count  Items\n--------  -----  -------------------------------------------------------\nHIGH        2    TLS not enabled (AMQP plaintext + Management HTTP);\n                 RabbitMQ 3.12.x is out of support / no security patches\nMEDIUM      3    app-user has full configure permission on /app;\n                 No HA/quorum policies; app-queue is classic (no HA);\n                 No message TTL / queue-length / DLX policies\nLOW         3    No vhost resource limits; no Kubernetes resource limits;\n                 credentials_obfuscation_fallback_secret is default value\nNOTE        2    loopback_users.guest=false (safe now, risky if guest\n                 re-created); etcd encryption status unknown\n\nNO CHANGES were made during this audit. All observations are read-only.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":553,"cache_read_input_tokens":37457,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":553},"output_tokens":11,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5fb079ae-f54d-4b57-aaf3-f58657c3fae1","uuid":"68f89815-4f31-4300-a2f5-43fe751ded26","request_id":"req_011Cc2hkyusDC4TKBPPEzZp9"}
