{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013czek3tnJQSmLwkecjpZrH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01PDe8XwxvLJrfGjqfwfbreB","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cat > /tmp/findings.txt << 'FINDINGS_EOF'\nRabbitMQ Read-Only Compliance Audit\n=====================================\nNamespace:  karma-rabbitmq-readonly-audit-20260614-064520\nAudit date: 2026-06-14\nAuditor:    Automated read-only inspection (no changes made)\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n1. CLUSTER HEALTH & TOPOLOGY\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nNodes (all disk nodes, all running):\n  rabbit@rabbitmq-0.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local\n  rabbit@rabbitmq-1.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local\n  rabbit@rabbitmq-2.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local\n\nActive alarms:        none\nNetwork partitions:   none\nMaintenance status:   no nodes under maintenance\nTotal memory used:    ~154 MB (watermark at 40% of available RAM, ~5.4 GB)\nFree disk space:      ~884 GB (watermark 50 MB)\nTotal connections:    0\nTotal queues:         1 (in /app)\n\n[OK] Cluster is healthy: 3/3 nodes running, no alarms, no partitions.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n2. VERSION & SUPPORT STATUS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nRabbitMQ version:   3.12.14   (image: rabbitmq:3.12-management)\nErlang/OTP version: 25.3.2.15\n\n[FINDING - HIGH] RabbitMQ 3.12 is out of support per the official release\ncalendar. No further security patches will be issued for this series. The\ncluster should be upgraded to a currently supported release series (3.13.x\nor 4.x at time of writing).\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n3. VIRTUAL HOSTS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nConfigured vhosts:\n  /       (default)\n  /app    (custom application vhost)\n\nNo vhost-level connection or queue-count limits are set on either vhost.\n\n[OK] Default vhost and application vhost are separated.\n[FINDING - LOW] No resource limits (max-connections, max-queues) are applied\nto either vhost, which could allow a single client to exhaust broker resources.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n4. USERS & TAGS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nUser        Tags\n----------  ----------------\nadmin       [administrator]\napp-user    (none)\n\nThe built-in \"guest\" user does not appear in the user list and has been\nremoved. This is correct practice.\n\n[OK] Only two users are defined; the default guest user is absent.\n[OK] admin is tagged as administrator; app-user carries no elevated tags.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n5. USER PERMISSIONS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nVhost / (default):\n  User     Configure  Write  Read\n  -------  ---------  -----  ----\n  admin    .*         .*     .*\n\nVhost /app:\n  User      Configure  Write  Read\n  --------  ---------  -----  ----\n  admin     .*         .*     .*\n  app-user  .*         .*     .*\n\n[OK] app-user has access only to /app, not to the default vhost.\n[FINDING - MEDIUM] app-user holds full configure permission (pattern \".*\") on\n/app. Application service accounts typically require only write + read access\nand should not be able to declare or delete exchanges, queues, or bindings at\nruntime. Consider tightening the configure pattern to \"\" (empty) or a narrow\nallowlist.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n6. POLICIES\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nNo policies are defined on either vhost (/ or /app).\n\n[FINDING - MEDIUM] Without policies there is no enforcement of:\n  - Queue high-availability / replication (classic queues have no HA\n    policy; see queue finding below).\n  - Message TTL (dead messages accumulate indefinitely).\n  - Queue length limits (unbounded growth possible under backpressure).\n  - Dead-letter routing (failed/expired messages are silently dropped).\nSecurity teams should confirm whether absence of these policies meets the\norganisation's data-retention and availability requirements.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n7. QUEUES\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nVhost /app:\n  Name       Type     Durable  State    Messages  Consumers\n  ---------  -------  -------  -------  --------  ---------\n  app-queue  classic  true     running  0         0\n\nVhost / (default): no queues.\n\n[OK] app-queue is durable -- it survives broker restarts.\n[FINDING - MEDIUM] app-queue is a classic (non-quorum) queue with no HA\npolicy. In a 3-node cluster this means queue data is stored on a single\nnode's disk; if that node fails, the queue and its messages are unavailable\nuntil the node recovers. For workloads requiring high availability, this\nqueue should be converted to a quorum queue (x-queue-type: quorum) or\ncovered by a classic mirroring policy. The quorum_queue feature flag is\nalready enabled on this cluster.\n\n[OK] No auto-delete queues are present.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n8. EXCHANGES (vhost /app)\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nOnly standard built-in AMQP exchanges are present -- no custom exchanges:\n  (default)          direct   durable\n  amq.direct         direct   durable\n  amq.fanout         fanout   durable\n  amq.headers        headers  durable\n  amq.match          headers  durable\n  amq.topic          topic    durable\n  amq.rabbitmq.trace topic    durable\n\n[OK] No unexpected or custom exchanges are defined.\n[NOTE] amq.rabbitmq.trace is always present but inactive unless explicitly\nactivated via rabbitmqctl trace_on. Confirm tracing is not active in\nproduction (would log all message payloads to the trace exchange).\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n9. TLS / ENCRYPTION IN TRANSIT\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nListeners configured:\n  Port 5672   protocol: amqp        (plaintext AMQP 0-9-1 and 1.0)\n  Port 15672  protocol: http        (plaintext HTTP Management API)\n  Port 25672  protocol: clustering  (inter-node / CLI)\n\nTLS listener list: [] (empty -- TLS is not enabled)\nSSL options:       [] (no certificate or CA paths configured)\n\n[FINDING - HIGH] AMQP traffic on port 5672 is unencrypted. All messages,\ncredentials (username + password sent on every connection), and channel\ndata are transmitted in plaintext. Any entity with network access can\nintercept or tamper with broker traffic.\n\n[FINDING - HIGH] The Management API (port 15672) is served over plain HTTP.\nAdmin credentials and API responses (which include full queue/user/policy\ndata) are exposed in plaintext.\n\nRecommended remediation: configure TLS listeners on 5671 (AMQPS) and 15671\n(HTTPS Management), supply a valid certificate/key pair via a Kubernetes\nSecret, and disable or restrict the plaintext listeners.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n10. AUTHENTICATION & SECURITY SETTINGS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nPassword hashing algorithm: rabbit_password_hashing_sha256  [OK]\n\nloopback_users.guest = false in rabbitmq.conf and 10-defaults.conf.\n  This setting means the guest user (if it existed) would be accessible\n  from any network host, not just loopback. The guest user has been\n  removed so there is no immediate risk, but this explicit \"false\" value\n  would be dangerous if guest were re-created.\n  [NOTE] Consider removing this override or setting loopback_users.guest =\n  true as a defence-in-depth measure.\n\ncredentials_obfuscation_fallback_secret = \"nocookie\" (the Erlang default).\n  [FINDING - LOW] The credential obfuscation fallback secret is set to the\n  default placeholder value. This should be rotated to a unique, randomly\n  generated value per deployment to strengthen at-rest obfuscation of\n  stored credentials.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n11. CLUSTER PARTITION HANDLING\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\ncluster_partition_handling = pause_minority\n\n[OK] pause_minority is the recommended setting for a 3-node cluster. The\nminority partition (1 node) pauses rather than forming a split-brain cluster,\npreserving data consistency at the expense of availability for that node.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n12. PLUGINS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nEnabled:\n  rabbitmq_management           -- HTTP API and web UI\n  rabbitmq_management_agent     -- per-node stats collection\n  rabbitmq_peer_discovery_k8s   -- Kubernetes-native cluster formation\n  rabbitmq_peer_discovery_common -- peer discovery base\n  rabbitmq_web_dispatch / cowboy / cowlib / amqp_client -- supporting libs\n\n[OK] No Shovel, Federation, LDAP, OAuth2, or Prometheus plugins are enabled.\n     Attack surface is minimal.\n[OK] Peer discovery uses the Kubernetes API (not static hostlists or DNS).\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n13. KUBERNETES RESOURCE LIMITS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nStatefulSet resource requests/limits: not set (resources: {})\n\n[FINDING - LOW] Without CPU and memory requests/limits the RabbitMQ pods can\nconsume unbounded node resources and may be OOM-killed under load without\npredictable behaviour. Define appropriate requests and limits for the\nproduction workload profile.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n14. SECRETS PRESENT IN NAMESPACE\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n  rabbitmq-admin          (Opaque, 2 keys -- admin credentials)\n  rabbitmq-app            (Opaque, 2 keys -- app-user credentials)\n  rabbitmq-erlang-cookie  (Opaque, 1 key  -- inter-node auth cookie)\n\n[OK] Credentials are stored as Kubernetes Secrets rather than embedded in\n     ConfigMaps or plain environment variables.\n[NOTE] Kubernetes Secrets are base64-encoded, not encrypted, unless etcd\nencryption is enabled at the cluster level. Confirm that etcd encryption is\nconfigured if at-rest encryption is a compliance requirement.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nSUMMARY OF FINDINGS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nSeverity  Count  Items\n--------  -----  -------------------------------------------------------\nHIGH        2    TLS not enabled: AMQP on 5672 is plaintext, Management\n                 API on 15672 is plain HTTP;\n                 RabbitMQ 3.12.14 is out of support (no security patches)\nMEDIUM      3    app-user has full configure permission on /app vhost;\n                 app-queue is classic type with no HA/quorum policy;\n                 No message TTL / queue-length / DLX policies on any vhost\nLOW         3    No vhost resource limits set;\n                 No Kubernetes CPU/memory resource limits on pods;\n                 credentials_obfuscation_fallback_secret is default value\nNOTE        2    loopback_users.guest=false is safe now but risky if guest\n                 is ever re-created; etcd encryption status unknown\n\nNO CHANGES were made during this audit. All observations are read-only.\nThe live cluster configuration is unchanged from how it was found.\nFINDINGS_EOF\necho \"Exit: $?\"","description":"Write findings report to /tmp/findings.txt"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4985,"cache_read_input_tokens":38010,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4985},"output_tokens":43,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5fb079ae-f54d-4b57-aaf3-f58657c3fae1","uuid":"3b264dd1-fe3b-423c-91a2-3cdf4f5154d8","request_id":"req_011Cc2hs1azHUEzoyxUjRS7v"}
